<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-485-587  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 485 587.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Oct 1 1990 v4 n35 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fincen sets up token-ring network for crime tracking. (FinancialCrimes Enforcement Network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (Fincen) of the US TreasuryDepartment installs a token-ring network comprised of 200 IBM PS/280s to maintain its crime tracking and analysis system.andP;  FincenDir Brian Bruh says that Fincen intends to develop additionalsophisticated computer tools for the network, including opticalcharacter recognition systems, text-based retrieval systems andCD-ROM systems.andP;  Fincen will use a chemical information retrievalsystem developed by the US Geological Survey that will allowinvestigators to enter any name into the system and search anumber of federal data bases.andP;  Fincen will address legal andregulatory issues that the amount of available data poses bycontrolling access to the information.andP;  Only select members ofindividual federal agencies will be authorized to obtain access tothe Fincen data base, and remote access will not be allowed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   IBM PS/2 80 (Microcomputer) (Usage).andO;Topic:     United States. Department of the TreasuryInstalling a ComputerFinancial Crimes Enforcement Network (Computer network)Token Ring NetworksApplicationsData BasesInformation Storage and RetrievalOn-Line SearchingSystem DevelopmentOffice AutomationGovernment Agency.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Brian Bruh. (portrait)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>